cal, yet increasingly expectant, of medicine, Americans struggled to cope with the paradoxes of sudden infant death; they worked to admit their powerlessness to prevent SIDS even while they tried to overcome it. Brittany Cowgill chronicles and assesses Americans' fraught but consequential efforts to explain and conquer SIDS, illuminating how and why SIDS has continued to cast a shadow over doctors and parents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInfantsxMortalityzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSudden infant death syndromexPrevention. 0aSudden infant death syndrome. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / General.2bisacsh  aSIDS.  aSudden Infant Death Syndrome.  ahistory.  ainfant death.  amedicine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311066608340uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813588223zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813588223423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813588223.jpg  a978-3-11-066608-3  Rutgers University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK